{{Infobox person |occupation=librarian and library scholar |alma_mater={{hlist|University of Pennsylvania|University of Chicago}} |awards=ALCTS Margaret Mann Citation, Ranganathan Award for Classification Research}} '''Elaine Svenonius''' is an American [[librarian]] and [[library scholar]], known for her research on [[bibliographic control]], particularly [[cataloging]], [[classification]], and [[Index (publishing)|indexing]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Elaine Svenonius|url=https://mitpress.mit.edu/authors/elaine-svenonius|publisher=The MIT Press|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> She is best known for bringing a philosophical [[knowledge organization]] approach to cataloging theory.
Svenonius received an MA in [[Philosophy]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1957, an MA in [[Library Science]] in 1965 from the [[University of Chicago]], and a [[PhD]] in Library Science in 1971, as well from the University of Chicago.<ref name=ccq />
In ''The Intellectual Foundation of Information Organization'', Svenonius attempts to "synthesize the literature of information organization in a language and at a level of generality to make it understandable to persons outside the field of library and information science" and to "synthesize subject and descriptive cataloging within a common conceptual framework." <ref name=ccq>{{cite journal|last=Myall|first=Carolynne|author2=McGarry, Dorothy |title=An Interview with Elaine Svenonius|journal=Cataloging & Classification Quarterly|volume=29|issue=4|pages=5–17|doi=10.1300/J104v29n04_02}}<!--|accessdate=31 May 2014--></ref> The book is frequently assigned to [[Master of Library and Information Science]] students, among whom it is nicknamed "the red devil".<ref>{{cite web|title=Intellectual Foundation of Information Organization|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/272799.Intellectual_Foundation_of_Information_Organization|work=Goodreads|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>
Svenonius was the recipient of the ALCTS Margaret Mann Citation<ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret Mann Citation|url=http://www.ala.org/Template.cfm?Section=awards&template=/ContentManagement/ContentDisplay.cfm&ContentID=74190|work=Awards|publisher=American Library Association|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> and the Ranganathan Award for Classification Research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Take note|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/990831honors|work=UCLA Today|accessdate=31 May 2014|date=31 August 1999}}</ref>
