{{italic title}} {{refimprove|date=June 2011}} {{Infobox book | name = Historical Dictionary of American Slang | title_orig = | translator = | image = Historical Dictionary of American Slang.jpg| caption = | author = Jonathan E. Lighter | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[United States]] | language = English | series = | subject = [[Slang]] | genre = [[Reference work]] | publisher = [[Random House]] | pub_date = 1994 (v.1), 1997 (v.2) | media_type = Print | pages = 1742 (first 2 vols.) | isbn = 0-394-54427-7 | dewey = 427.973 | congress = PE 2846 .H57 1994 | oclc = 30029055 }}
The '''''Historical Dictionary of American Slang''''', often abbreviated '''''HDAS''''', is a [[dictionary]] of American [[slang]]. The first two volumes, ''Volume 1, A – G'' (1994), and ''Volume 2, H – O'' (1997), were published by [[Random House]], and the work then was known as the '''''Random House Historical Dictionary of American Slang''''', sometimes abbreviated as '''''RHHDAS'''''. Both volumes used the same ISBN, {{ISBN|0-394-54427-7}}; the paperback editions are {{ISBN|978-0-394-54427-4}} for Volume 1 and {{ISBN|978-0-679-43464-1}} for Volume 2.
When Random House discontinued publication, [[Oxford University Press]] announced in 2003 that it would publish the two remaining volumes, ''Volume 3, P – S [Part 1]'', {{ISBN|978-0-19-517418-2}}, and ''Volume 4, S [Part 2] – Z''. <ref name="oup">{{cite web| title=Historical Dictionary of American Slang: Project History|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=http://www.oup.com/us/collections/slang/history/?view=usa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017212817/http://www.oup.com/us/collections/slang/history/?view=usa|archive-date=2012-10-17|access-date=2016-05-17|dead-url=yes}}</ref> As of 2018, however, those volumes have not yet been published.
Each entry includes representative quotations, including the earliest quotation using the word. HDAS is edited by Jonathan E. Lighter of the [[University of Tennessee]]. It is sometimes compared to ''[[Green's Dictionary of Slang]]'', which takes a generally similar approach but is not focused specifically on American slang.
The ''HDAS'' is not to be confused with the ''DAS'', the ''Dictionary of American Slang'' (1975).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Dictionary_of_American_slang.html?id=P6MYAAAAIAAJ |title=Dictionary of American slang - Harold Wentworth, Stuart Berg Flexner - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/dictionary/d4ction.html |title=Dictionaries and Works Cited: Dictionary of Newfoundland English |publisher=Heritage.nf.ca |date= |accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>
