The '''New Annual Register''' (subtitled, "Or General Repository of History, Politics and Literature for the Year...") was an annual [[Reference book|reference work]], founded in 1780 by [[Andrew Kippis]] in [[London, England]]. It recorded and analysed the year's major events, developments and trends, throughout the world, as a rival to the ''[[Annual Register]]'' appearing from 1758, under the editorship of [[Edmund Burke]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=11463|title=Gregory, George|first=Philip|last=Carter}}</ref> After Kippis died in 1795 it was taken on by Thomas Morgan (1752–1821).<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Watt|title=Bibliotheca britannica; or, A general index to British and foreign literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=swMJAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA683|accessdate=14 March 2013|year=1824|publisher=Printed for A. Constable and Company|page=683}}</ref> [[George Gregory (British writer)|George Gregory]] edited it, and changed its Whig politics to Tory at the time of the [[Addington ministry]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=11463|title=Gregory, George|first=Philip|last=Carter}}</ref> It was published until 1825.<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Charles Henry Timperley]]|title=The Dictionary of Printer and Printing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmxTMABJ9q4C&pg=PA748|accessdate=14 March 2013|year=1839|publisher=H. Johnson|page=748}}</ref>
The ''Register'' was published by [[George Robinson (bookseller)|George Robinson]] from 1781.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=74586|title=Robinson family|first=G. E.|last=Bentley}}</ref> From 1784 to 1791 [[William Godwin]] was writing the British historical section.<ref>Marken.</ref>
==References== *Jack W. Marken, ''William Godwin's Writing for the New Annual Register'', Modern Language Notes Vol. 68, No. 7 (Nov., 1953), pp.&nbsp;477–479. Published by: The Johns Hopkins University Press. Stable URL: https://www.jstor.org/stable/3043660
