{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Zuniga at the Hirshhorn.jpg | painting_alignment = left side | image_size = 200px | title = Seated Yucatán Woman | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = Francisco Zúñiga | year = 1973 | type = [[Bronze]] | height_metric = 105.4 | width_metric = 89.9 | length_metric = 114.0 | height_imperial = {{frac|41|1|2}} | width_imperial = {{frac|35|3|8}} | length_imperial = {{frac|44|7|8}} | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]] | museum = | coordinates = {{coord|38.889117|-77.022683|region:US_type:landmark| }} | owner = [[Smithsonian Institution]] }} '''''Seated Yucatán Woman''''' is a bronze sculpture, by [[Francisco Zúñiga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!373165~!0#focu |title=Seated Yucatan Woman, (sculpture) |publisher=Siris-artinventories.si.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-03-11}}</ref> It is an edition of four, one of which is located at the [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hirshhorn.si.edu/visit/collection_object.asp?key=32&subkey=14673 |title=Collection Search - Hirshhorn Museum &#124; Smithsonian |publisher=Hirshhorn.si.edu |date=2010-12-07 |accessdate=2015-03-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090402065223/http://www.hirshhorn.si.edu/visit/collection_object.asp?key=32&subkey=14673 |archivedate=2009-04-02 |df= }}</ref>
The artist depicts the grace and dignity of peasant women in Mexico.<ref>''A Garden for Art'', Valerie J. Fletcher, OCLC 97-61991, p.59</ref>
According to Ariel Zuñiga, the correct title of the piece is ''Juchiteca sentada (Seated Juchiteca)''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/hirshhorn/hirshhorn7.html |title=Images of sculpture from The Hirshhorn Sculpture Gardens-page 7. Digital Imaging Project: Art historical images of European and North American architecture and sculpture from classical Greek to Post-modern. Scanned from slides taken on site by Mary Ann Sullivan, Bluffton College |publisher=Bluffton.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-03-11}}</ref>
