{{italic title}}
{{no-footnotes|date=November 2015}}
The '''''Synecdemus''''' or '''''Synekdemos''''' ({{lang-el|Συνέκδημος}}) is a geographic text, attributed to [[Hierocles (author of Synecdemus)|Hierocles]], which contains a table of administrative divisions of the [[Byzantine Empire]] and lists of their cities. The work is dated to the reign of [[Justinian]] but prior to 535, as it divides the 912 listed cities in the Empire among 64 [[Eparchy|Eparchies]]. The ''Synecdemus'', along with the work of [[Stephanus of Byzantium]] were the principal sources of [[Constantine VII]]'s work on the Themes (''De Thematibus''). 

The ''Synecdemus'' was published in various editions beginning in 1735, notably by [[Gustav Parthey]] (''Hieroclis Synecdemus''; Berlin, 1866) and slightly later in a corrected text by A. Burckhardt in the [[Teubner]] series.<ref name="(Grammarian.)East)1893">{{cite book|author1=Hierocles (Grammarian.)|author2=Constantine VII Porphyrogenitus (Emperor of the East)|first3=August |last3=Burckhardt|title=Hieroclis Synecdemus: accedunt fragmenta apud Constantinum Porphyrogennetum servata et nomina urbium mutata|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=HIITK93F54wC}}|year=1893|publisher=in aedibus B.G. Teubneri}}</ref> The most recent major publication was by E. Honigmann (Le Synekdèmos d'Hiéroklès et l'opuscule géographique de Georges de Chypre; Brussels, 1939).

