{{italic title}}
[[Image:Wakan Sansai Zue Ashika & Ottosei.gif|thumb|150px|[[Sea lion]] (right) and [[fur seal]], ''Wakan Sansai Zue'', vol 38 p. 72, (ca. 1712).]]

The {{nihongo||和漢三才図会|'''Wakan Sansai Zue'''|lit. "Illustrated Sino-Japanese Encyclopedia"}} is an illustrated [[Japan]]ese ''[[leishu]]'' encyclopedia published in 1712 in the [[Edo period]]. It consists of 105 volumes in 81 books. Its compiler was [[Terashima]] or [[Terajima Ryōan|Terajima]] ({{Nihongo|Terajima Ryōan|寺島良安|}}), a doctor from [[Osaka]]. It describes and illustrates various activities of daily life, such as [[carpentry]] and [[fishing]], as well as [[plants]] and [[animals]], and [[constellations]]. As seen from the title of the book ([[Wa (Japan)|和 (wa)]], which means Japan and ([[Han Dynasty|漢 (kan)]], which means China), Terajima's idea was based on a [[Chinese encyclopedia]], specifically the [[Ming Dynasty|Ming]] work ''[[Sancai Tuhui]]'' ("Pictorial..." or "Illustrated Compendium of the Three Powers") by [[Wang Qi]] (1607), known in Japan as the {{nihongo|''Sansai Zue''|三才図会|}}. Reproductions of the ''Wakan Sansai Zue'' are still in print in Japan.

